       <div class="block block-views first odd module clearfix" id="block-views-homepage-feed-block">
        <h2 class="block__title block-title">
         Latest News and Announcements
        </h2>
        <div class="block-content">
         <div class="view view-homepage-feed view-id-homepage_feed view-display-id-block announcements view-dom-id-feb753cccbe81440f98e4ca249479b7a">
          <div class="feed-icon">
           <div class="ss-icon rss-icon">
            <a href="http://physical-sciences.uchicago.edu/rss.xml" title="Subscribe to Latest News and Announcements">
             RSS
            </a>
           </div>
          </div>
          <div class="view-content">
           <div class="views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first">
            <h3>
             Scientists drill into Taylor Glacier in Antarctica to understand past climate change
            </h3>
            <p lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">
             In a
             <a href="https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1029/2018GL081887" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">
              new study
             </a>
             led by UChicago postdoctoral researcher, Sarah Aarons, scientists found that volcanic dust embedded inside
             <a href="https://news.uchicago.edu/story/glacier-tree-rings-could-hold-clues-planets-future" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">
              ice samples
             </a>
             suggests that the West Antarctic Ice Sheet collapsed during the last warm period 130,000 years ago.
            </p>
            <p>
             <a href="/news/scientists-drill-taylor-glacier-antarctica-understand-past-climate-change">
              Read the full post
             </a>
            </p>
            <hr/>
           </div>
           <div class="views-row views-row-2 views-row-even">
            <h3>
             Breakthrough could enable infrared cameras for electronics, self-driving cars
            </h3>
            <p lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">
             UChicago scientists made a
             <a href="https://news.uchicago.edu/story/breakthrough-could-enable-infrared-cameras-electronics-self-driving-cars" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">
              new breakthrough
             </a>
             in manufacturing infrared cameras, using quantum dots instead of multiple layers of semiconductors.
            </p>
            <p>
             <a href="/news/breakthrough-could-enable-infrared-cameras-electronics-self-driving-cars">
              Read the full post
             </a>
            </p>
            <hr/>
           </div>
           <div class="views-row views-row-3 views-row-odd">
            <h3>
             The new MADD center to host a workshop on soft, stretchable electronics
            </h3>
            <p lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">
             On March 12, a workshop in the new
             <a href="https://arts.uchicago.edu/explore/initiatives/media-arts-data-and-design-center-madd-center" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">
              Media Arts, Data and Design (MADD) Center
             </a>
             in John Crerar Library will teach students a DIY (do it yourself) method for making
             <a href="https://www.cs.uchicago.edu/news/article/cs-madd-center-workshop-introduces-diy-soft-stretchable-electronics/" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">
              stretchable electronics
             </a>
             with silicone and liquid metal.
            </p>
            <p>
             <a href="/news/new-madd-center-host-workshop-soft-stretchable-electronics">
              Read the full post
             </a>
            </p>
            <hr/>
           </div>
           <div class="views-row views-row-4 views-row-even">
            <h3>
             IBM and University of Chicago collaborate to advance quantum computing
            </h3>
            <p lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">
             A new
             <a href="https://phys.org/wire-news/313346439/ibm-and-university-of-chicago-collaborate-to-advance-quantum-com.html" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">
              research collaboration
             </a>
             between the Enabling Practical-Scale Quantum Computing (
             <a href="https://www.epiqc.cs.uchicago.edu/" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">
              EPiQC
             </a>
             ) project led by the University of Chicago and IBM will help bring the promising future of quantum computing closer to the present.
            </p>
            <p>
             <a href="/news/ibm-and-university-chicago-collaborate-advance-quantum-computing-0">
              Read the full post
             </a>
            </p>
            <hr/>
           </div>
           <div class="views-row views-row-5 views-row-odd">
            <h3>
             Physicists use sound to reveal how particles cluster together in the absence of gravity
            </h3>
            <p lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">
             In their
             <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41567-019-0440-9" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">
              study
             </a>
             , UChicago and University of Bath physicists used
             <a href="https://news.uchicago.edu/story/scientists-levitate-particles-sound-find-out-how-they-cluster-together" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">
              sound waves
             </a>
             to levitate plastic particles in midair to study how these particles interact with each other as they formed clusters, broke up, and then reassembled into different configurations.
            </p>
            <p>
             <a href="/news/physicists-use-sound-reveal-how-particles-cluster-together-absence-gravity">
              Read the full post
             </a>
            </p>
            <hr/>
           </div>
           <div class="views-row views-row-6 views-row-even">
            <h3>
             Justin Kasper discusses his work on Parker Solar Probe and developing instruments for NASA
            </h3>
            <p lang="EN-US" xml:lang="EN-US">
             Meet a UChicagoan: Justin Kasper, AB'99, heads a team that built a
